INTERNET

The Internet is a global network of computers connected to each other which communicate through a standardized set of protocols.



HOW IT WORK
 It allows people all over the world to share information, communicate with each other, and access a wide range of services and resources.

Here's a simplified explanation of how the Internet works:

You connect to the Internet: When you connect to the Internet, your device (such as a computer, tablet, or smartphone) sends a request to your Internet Service Provider (ISP) to establish a connection.

Your ISP connects you to the Internet: Your ISP provides you with a unique IP address and connects your device to the Internet through its own network.

Your device sends and receives data: Once connected, your device can send and receive data over the Internet using standardized communication protocols, such as Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) and Internet Protocol (IP).

Data is broken up into packets: When data is sent over the Internet, it is broken up into small packets that are sent from one device to another until they reach their destination.

Routers direct packets to their destination: As the packets travel across the Internet, they pass through many different routers, which direct them to their intended destination based on the IP address of the destination device.

The data is reassembled: Once all the packets reach their destination, they are reassembled into the original data and can be accessed by the recipient.

This process happens countless times per second all over the world, allowing people to share information, communicate with each other, and access a wide range of services and resources.


