A web browser is a software application that allows users to access and view web pages on the internet. Here's a simplified overview of how a web browser works:

A user types a URL (Uniform Resource Locator) into the browser's address bar, or clicks on a link on a web page or in an email.

The browser sends a request to the server hosting the website, asking for the specific web page or resource that the user wants to access.

The server responds with the requested web page, which includes HTML (Hypertext Markup Language) code, CSS (Cascading Style Sheets), JavaScript, images, and other assets.

The browser then begins to render the web page, starting with the HTML code. The browser's rendering engine parses the HTML code and creates a Document Object Model (DOM) tree, which represents the structure of the web page.

The browser then applies the CSS styles to the DOM tree, which determines how the web page looks and how its elements are positioned on the screen.

The browser also executes any JavaScript code on the web page, which can add interactivity and dynamic behavior to the web page.

Finally, the browser displays the fully rendered web page to the user, including any images, videos, and other multimedia content.



DOMAIN  NAME

A domain name is a unique name that is used to identify a website on the internet. It is the human-readable address that you type into your web browser to access a website


A domain name consists of two main parts: the top-level domain (TLD) and the second-level domain (SLD). The TLD is the part of the domain name that comes after the dot (such as .com, .org, .net, etc.), while the SLD is the part that comes before the dot (such as example in www.example.com).

HOSTING


Web hosting is an online service that allows you to publish your website files onto the internet. So, anyone who has access to the internet has access to your website.


Shared Hosting:where multiple websites are hosted on a single server. Resources such as disk space, bandwidth, and memory are shared among the websites, making it cost-effective but not suitable for high-traffic websites.

Virtual Private Server (VPS) Hosting: This type of hosting provides a dedicated amount of resources to a website by dividing a physical server into multiple virtual servers. Each VPS acts as an independent server, providing users with more control, customization, and scalability.

Dedicated Hosting: In this type of hosting, the website is hosted on a dedicated physical server. This gives website owners complete control over the server and its resources, making it ideal for high-traffic websites that require high performance, security, and customization.

Cloud Hosting: Cloud hosting utilizes a network of servers to host websites and distribute resources dynamically. It is highly scalable and flexible, making it suitable for websites that experience fluctuations in traffic.

Managed Hosting: This type of hosting is similar to dedicated hosting, but with the added benefit of management services. Managed hosting providers handle tasks such as server maintenance, security, backups, and software updates, allowing website owners to focus on their business.

Reseller Hosting: Reseller hosting allows users to resell hosting services to other businesses or clients. This is an excellent option for web designers, developers, and agencies who want to offer hosting as part of their services.

Shared Hosting vs. VPS Hosting vs. Dedicated Server




Web accessibility means that websites, tools, and technologies are designed and developed in such a way that people with disabilities can use them easily.

A package manager is a software tool that helps you to easily install, update, and remove software packages (also known as "libraries" or "dependencies") on your computer





